# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# membrane-graphic-kernel.form — the boundary axiom worn as skin
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# The boundary axiom (core-axioms.form, axiom 4) says every cell has a
# membrane: the surface where inside meets outside, where offers cross.
# This recipe names how that membrane becomes VISIBLE — a graphic
# kernel, generated from the cell's inner state, running natively on
# the GPU. The matvec-emitter teaching (a Form recipe that emits native
# code) carried to graphics: a recipe that emits a fragment program.
#
# Running carrier today: web/lib/form-kernel/membrane.ts
#   buildMembraneShaders() — assembles ONE GLSL kernel from a field
#   table; encodeMembraneState() — packs a cell's inner state as data.
# The carrier is TS because the GPU door (WebGL) lives in the browser;
# the SHAPE below is the Form body the carrier expresses. When the
# kernels grow a WGSL/compute door, this recipe is the blueprint the
# emitter realizes — same field table, same data feed, new carrier.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 1 — the inner state that textures the boundary
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# A membrane's appearance is a projection of exactly three readings of
# the cell it bounds — nothing decorative, every channel a measurement:
#
#   blueprint-seed     hash(blueprint NodeID) — structural identity.
#                      Two structurally-equivalent cells wear the SAME
#                      skin pattern anywhere in the space. Ice, worn.
#
#   category-mix       normalized histogram of the subtree's Form
#                      categories (MATH, FNCALL, COND, WITNESS, ...).
#                      The inner composition blends the texture fields.
#
#   pores              one site per child, golden-spiral placed, seeded
#                      by instance identity. A pore carries the child's
#                      color, runtime heat, and kind. Doors attach AT
#                      their pores: offers cross the boundary at named
#                      sites, and the door's beam and the pore's glow
#                      are one geometry computed once, read twice
#                      (JS lays the beam; the GPU draws the glow).

(defn membrane_state (cell)
  (list
    (blueprint_seed (hash (.blueprint cell)))
    (category_mix (histogram (map .category (subtree cell))))
    (pores (map_indexed
      (fn (i child)
        (pore (golden_spiral i (arity cell) (hash (.id cell)))
              (.color child) (.heat child) (.kind child)))
      (.children cell)))))

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 2 — one kernel, fields as data
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# There is ONE membrane program. Per-cell variation arrives as data
# (uniforms + a 32×2 texel feed), never as parallel shader paths.
# The fragment kernel is ASSEMBLED from a field table — each Form
# category family contributes a procedural texture vocabulary:
#
#   MATH / COMPARE      → interference   (standing waves meeting)
#   LIST / ACCESS       → strata         (ordered banding, shelves)
#   FNCALL / CALL       → spiral         (recursion winding inward)
#   COND / CHOICE       → veins          (bifurcating decision paths)
#   WITNESS / OBSERVER  → iris           (concentric attention rings)
#   IDENT / ALIAS       → filament       (name-threads, script strands)
#   BLOCK               → sediment       (statement layers)
#   otherwise           → cellular       (voronoi tissue, the ground)
#
# Adding a vocabulary is adding a ROW, not a branch. The kernel mixes
# the fields by the category histogram at runtime — a MATH-heavy cell
# shimmers with interference; a recursive cell wears spirals.

(defn membrane_kernel (field_table)
  (emit_fragment
    (concat
      (map (fn (field) (emit_field_fn field)) field_table)
      (emit_mix field_table)      ; Σ weight_i · field_i(p, seed, t)
      (emit_pore_loop)            ; glow + ripple at each child's site
      (emit_fresnel_rim)          ; the living edge, iridescent by seed
      (emit_inner_projection))))  ; the gl_FrontFacing branch, Part 3

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 3 — both sides of the boundary
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# A membrane has two faces and the kernel renders both:
#
#   outside (front-facing)  the skin — category texture over the
#                           blueprint-seeded warp; pores glowing their
#                           children through; heat breathing the whole
#                           surface; a touch-ripple when focus lands.
#
#   inside (back-facing)    the planetarium — the inner projection.
#                           Pores become windows; the category nebula
#                           intensifies; and the substrate lattice
#                           framebuffer belts the equator: the body's
#                           memory plane, projected on the boundary's
#                           own inner skin. Stepping into a cell is
#                           stepping into what it knows.
#
# GAP: the lattice belt currently projects the client-side TS-kernel
# lattice. When the Go kernel's /api/_form/ideas-observation feed
# streams into the page, the same uniform door carries the production
# framebuffer — no kernel change, new data.
